17:49.735 --> 17:53.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know that presidents often
have to deal
with unsavory characters and
sometimes that

17:54.006 --> 17:58.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there is a strategic goal in
putting your
arm around someone who you may
personally

17:58.177 --> 18:01.647 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
feel is a reprehensible human
being.

18:01.680 --> 18:03.048 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Couldn't there be a strategic
interest?

18:03.082 --> 18:05.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, couldn't this really
just be about
North Korea?

18:05.617 --> 18:07.719 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID KRAMER: Well, for sure.

18:07.753 --> 18:10.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those of us in the human rights
community
have never argued that human
rights should

18:10.889 --> 18:13.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drown out other interests the
United States
has.

18:13.692 --> 18:18.130 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We have energy, economic
interests with countries,
security interests, but we also
have democracy,

18:18.163 --> 18:19.932 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
human rights interests with
countries.

18:19.965 --> 18:24.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And our argument is that that
last set of
interests shouldn't be
shortchanged in the

18:24.870 --> 18:26.738 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
pursuit of these other
interests.

18:26.772 --> 18:30.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Let's say
President Trump
did speak out and somehow
condemned what Duterte

18:30.809 --> 18:33.445 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has been doing or been involved
in.

18:33.479 --> 18:37.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Isn't there a risk, given
Duterte's personality,
that we could jeopardize the
Philippines as

18:37.816 --> 18:40.285 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an ally, who are a very crucial
ally to us?

18:40.319 --> 18:43.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Isn't there a risk that he could
sully that
relationship?

18:43.155 --> 18:44.957 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID KRAMER: There is a risk.

18:44.990 --> 18:48.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we saw this last year when
President Obama
indicated he was going to raise
human rights

18:48.727 --> 18:54.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issues if he had met with
Duterte, and Duterte
responded with an epithet toward
the president,

18:54.766 --> 18:58.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and basically said he was going
to turn to
China and Russia.

18:58.170 --> 19:03.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that's a little more
bluff, even though
today there were Chinese naval
vessels in

19:03.642 --> 19:06.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a port in the Philippines that
Duterte himself
visited.

19:06.512 --> 19:10.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, at the end of the day, the
Philippines-American
relationship is longstanding.

19:10.849 --> 19:15.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have very strong ties between
our peoples,
our countries and our
governments.

19:15.921 --> 19:20.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think it's important to
use those ties
as leverage to insist and press
for better

19:20.926 --> 19:23.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
treatment of the people of the
Philippines.

19:23.428 --> 19:25.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Last quick
question.

19:25.597 --> 19:28.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump today also said
that he would
meet with the North Korean
leader.

19:28.600 --> 19:30.302 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How does that sit with you?

19:30.335 --> 19:33.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID KRAMER: I would hope that
that would
be a last resort after
everything else is

19:33.405 --> 19:35.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
tried at lower levels.

19:35.307 --> 19:40.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Granting an audience to the
worst abuser of
human rights, the North Korean
leader, President

19:40.445 --> 19:43.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kim, is something I would hope
we don't see
any time soon.

19:43.949 --> 19:49.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The problem is, obviously, not
just nuclear
concerns, nuclear security, but
also the treatment

19:50.022 --> 19:52.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of North Korean people by its
leader.

19:52.758 --> 19:54.126 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That is a huge problem.

19:54.159 --> 19:56.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I hope that would also not
get swept under
the rug.

19:56.862 --> 20:01.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
David Kramer
of the McCain Institute, thank
you very much.

20:01.300 --> 20:08.207 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID KRAMER: Thank you.

20:08.240 --> 20:14.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The world's
youngest country
is tearing itself apart.

20:14.813 --> 20:19.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
South Sudan was founded in 2011,
but, two
years later, forces allied to
the president

20:19.585 --> 20:22.287 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and vice president began
fighting each other.

20:22.321 --> 20:25.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That civil war has now led to
the near collapse
of the country.

20:25.757 --> 20:29.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In partnership with the Pulitzer
Center on
Crisis Reporting, special
correspondent Jane

20:29.928 --> 20:33.432 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ferguson begins a series of
three reports.

20:33.465 --> 20:36.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight is a look at this brutal
war and its
tribal roots.

20:36.602 --> 20:40.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a warning: Some images and
stories in
this report are disturbing.

20:40.839 --> 20:45.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: This was once a
busy market
town.

20:45.711 --> 20:51.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Villagers from the countryside
would come
to Leer to trade goods and catch
up on news.

20:51.049 --> 20:53.485 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Now there is no one.

20:53.518 --> 20:58.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All the people have fled into
the bush, hiding
from violent raids by government
soldiers.

20:58.690 --> 21:02.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We found some of them a few
miles away in
rebel-held land.

21:03.028 --> 21:07.599 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They had crept out of hiding to
get help from
aid agencies.

21:07.633 --> 21:10.402 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Without it, they will starve.

21:10.435 --> 21:13.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their stories of what they have
endured are
horrifying.

21:13.639 --> 21:18.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): The
government is
killing men, women and children,
and sometimes

21:18.577 --> 21:22.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they even cook the dead bodies
and force us
to eat them.

21:22.914 --> 21:27.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My 5-year-old daughter was
slaughtered, and
they made me eat her body.

21:27.786 --> 21:32.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Tales of such
brutality are
common in South Sudan's civil
war.

21:32.190 --> 21:38.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A fallout between president
Salva Kiir and
his vice president, Riek Machar,
began in

21:38.363 --> 21:42.401 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
2013, tearing the country along
tribal lines.

21:42.434 --> 21:49.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kiir is from the Dinka tribe,
Machar from
the rival Nuer tribe.

21:49.241 --> 21:52.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fighting between the two sides
soon involved
other subtribes.

21:52.644 --> 21:56.948 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Battles broke out across the
country.

21:56.982 --> 22:03.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Murderous raids on civilian
communities are
a favored tactic, according to
Jonathan Pedneault

22:03.889 --> 22:05.724 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of Human Rights Watch.

22:05.757 --> 22:08.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JONATHAN PEDNEAULT, Human Rights
Watch: Both
opposition and government
fighters see various

22:08.293 --> 22:12.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
specific ethnic groups as being
supportive
of their -- either of their
opponents.

22:12.364 --> 22:15.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in order to decrease the
military capacities
of their opponents, they decide
to target

22:15.167 --> 22:18.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
civilians, because, without
civilians, those
fighters won't have a place to
stay, they

22:18.236 --> 22:23.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
won't receive food, they won't
receive popular
support.

22:23.475 --> 22:32.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, the aim by targeting
civilians is, in
effect, to cut the grass under
the feet of

22:32.918 --> 22:34.119 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
those fighters.

22:34.152 --> 22:38.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: This is what
ethnic cleansing
looks like.

22:38.857 --> 22:44.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Entire populations of specific
tribes are
being forced out of areas in
South Sudan.

22:44.563 --> 22:47.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Malakal town was a mixture of
tribes.

22:47.899 --> 22:52.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Government and opposition forces
have been
fighting over it throughout the
war, both

22:52.404 --> 22:53.972 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
committing atrocities.

22:54.005 --> 22:59.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Each time the town changed
hands, civilians
of a specific tribe were
targeted.

22:59.878 --> 23:04.049 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's now controlled by Dinka
government soldiers.

23:04.082 --> 23:09.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Entire neighborhoods, where the
Nuer and other
tribes at risk used to live, lay
silent and

23:09.554 --> 23:14.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
empty, the grass reclaiming
streets that used
to be home for so many.

23:14.526 --> 23:17.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are not allowed to get out
and film in
the town center.

23:17.629 --> 23:23.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's lots of police and army
around, but
what there aren't are civilians
who live here.

23:23.201 --> 23:26.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This was once South Sudan's
second biggest
city.

23:26.071 --> 23:30.475 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And the streets and
neighborhoods are completely
abandoned now.

23:30.509 --> 23:35.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Civilians are fleeing towns and
cities across
South Sudan because of repeated
attacks.

23:35.280 --> 23:38.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they're just turning into
ghost towns.

23:38.850 --> 23:42.053 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They ran to this camp just
outside the town.

23:42.087 --> 23:48.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is a dusty, miserable place,
where sewage
runs between shacks and
desperately poor survivors

23:48.260 --> 23:51.863 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the violence try to go on
living.

23:51.897 --> 23:54.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Elizabeth is one of them.

23:54.199 --> 23:59.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A single mother of six, she
sells cups of
tea in the camp to earn some
money.

24:00.005 --> 24:04.342 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the memory of what happened
in the town
is always with her.

24:04.376 --> 24:09.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELIZABETH SHOL ROUT, South Sudan
(through
translator): I saw many people
killed, including

24:09.748 --> 24:11.349 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
my brother.

24:11.383 --> 24:14.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They called my brother to come
out of the
house and shot him in front of
me.

24:14.553 --> 24:20.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: The only thing
standing between
her and the government soldiers
are U.N. peacekeeping

24:20.826 --> 24:22.594 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
soldiers.

24:22.627 --> 24:28.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They guard this camp and others
like it across
South Sudan, trying to stop more
massacres.

24:28.900 --> 24:34.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.N. said in December in a
statement South
Sudan is on the brink of all-out
genocide,

24:34.940 --> 24:37.943 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
similar to what happened in
Rwanda in 1994.

24:37.976 --> 24:44.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And yet its peacekeepers seem
unwilling or
unable to stop it.

24:44.216 --> 24:49.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last year, government soldiers
forced their
way into the camp, and over
several days murdered

24:49.521 --> 24:54.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more than 25 people and injured
and raped
many others.

24:54.259 --> 24:56.895 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Elizabeth shows us where they
came in.

24:56.928 --> 25:00.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She remains bitter that the U.N.
soldiers
didn't stop them.

25:00.599 --> 25:04.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ELIZABETH (through translator):
They did nothing.

25:04.703 --> 25:08.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When they saw the soldiers cut
the fence and
come into the camp, they just
opened the gate

25:08.874 --> 25:10.542 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to allow the people to escape.

25:10.575 --> 25:16.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: There are over
13,000 U.N.
peacekeeping soldiers in South
Sudan.

25:16.047 --> 25:21.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More than 200,000 civilians have
fled to their
bases across the country when
targeted by

25:21.453 --> 25:28.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the violence, forcing the U.N.
to create guarded
camps in order to protect the
people.

25:28.326 --> 25:33.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Despite having authority to use
force if needed
to stop attacks against
civilians, the peacekeepers

25:33.665 --> 25:38.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have come under criticism for
not doing so
when attacks have happened in
front of them.

25:38.737 --> 25:42.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOUSTAPHA SOUMARE, United
Nations: Peacekeeping,
and that's all it is.

25:43.008 --> 25:45.443 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's really you keep peace.

25:45.477 --> 25:52.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, normally, the people who
come in peacekeeping,
the troops and so on, are really
prepared

25:52.117 --> 25:55.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the spirit of peacekeeping,
not really
entering into direct fight.

25:55.754 --> 26:00.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Despite this, he
says the U.N.
have now pushed their forces to
improve.

26:00.358 --> 26:06.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOUSTAPHA SOUMARE: They have
been instructed
that, if you see something like
that, you

26:06.331 --> 26:07.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
make a warning shot.

26:08.033 --> 26:13.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If people are -- really not
responded, you
can actually use your firearm on
that.

26:13.438 --> 26:18.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: South Sudan is
the world's
youngest nation, and the
international community

26:18.343 --> 26:21.446 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
played a major part in its
creation.

26:21.479 --> 26:27.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After decades of devastating
civil war with
the North, South Sudan finally
won its independence

26:27.352 --> 26:30.555 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with a referendum in 2011.

26:30.589 --> 26:35.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
American church groups and
politicians had
campaigned for the peaceful
birth of the nation

26:35.360 --> 26:37.228 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for years.

26:37.262 --> 26:42.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it was South Sudanese
fighters, community
leaders and advocates who
sacrificed so much

26:42.901 --> 26:45.937 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to see this country find its
freedom.

26:45.971 --> 26:47.739 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
One of them was Alfred Taban.

26:47.772 --> 26:53.211 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
A veteran journalist and
newspaper editor,
he was jailed and tortured
repeatedly for

26:53.244 --> 26:56.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years in the northern capital of
Khartoum
for calling for independence.

26:56.715 --> 27:00.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALFRED TABAN, Journalist: Well,
I knew we
were going to succeed.

27:00.585 --> 27:11.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I knew we had not -- we had not
done anything
bad.

27:11.863 --> 27:17.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We were struggling for our
rights as human
beings.

27:17.636 --> 27:26.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's what led me to
survive.

27:26.711 --> 27:28.947 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I knew we will succeed.

27:28.980 --> 27:35.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: After sacrificing
so much for
his country, its rapid descent
into civil

27:35.220 --> 27:37.522 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
war has broken his heart.

27:37.555 --> 27:43.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALFRED TABAN: The killing of one
another started,
the Nuers being killed, the
Dinkas being killed

27:43.828 --> 27:50.335 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and other tribes, then I knew
things had really
gone bad.

27:50.368 --> 27:57.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then I knew that partly we -- or
they themselves,
they were not only struggling
for the people,

27:57.275 --> 28:02.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but they were struggling for
themselves to
lead or to rule.

28:02.047 --> 28:04.549 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I became very, very
disappointed.

28:04.582 --> 28:09.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: In frustration,
he wrote a
column in the newspaper he runs
calling for

28:09.688 --> 28:14.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the leaders of both sides in
this war to step
down.

28:14.059 --> 28:19.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Shortly after, the government he
sacrificed
his freedom for jailed him for
nearly two

28:19.898 --> 28:21.132 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
weeks.

28:21.166 --> 28:23.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALFRED TABAN: They were not
struggling for
their people.

28:23.201 --> 28:26.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They were struggling for
themselves.

28:26.204 --> 28:31.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is why really the
struggle of the
people of South Sudan has been
hijacked from

28:31.976 --> 28:34.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the very beginning.

28:34.379 --> 28:42.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It has become a struggle for
position and
wealth, not a struggle for the
betterment

28:42.587 --> 28:46.291 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the lives of the people of
South Sudan.

28:46.324 --> 28:50.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Yet neither side
