But first: A new investigative
report finds
a disturbing pattern.

29:50.088 --> 29:55.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sexual abuse of students by
other students
happens more frequently in
schools than reported,

29:55.627 --> 29:59.097 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the consequences for the
offenders vary
considerably.

29:59.130 --> 30:00.965 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story.

30:00.999 --> 30:05.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A hidden horror
educators have
long been warned not to ignore
-- that's the

30:05.937 --> 30:10.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
description of sexual abuse in
schools by
the Associated Press, which
published its

30:10.575 --> 30:12.210 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
story today.

30:12.243 --> 30:16.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AP Reporters found that students
were seven
times more likely than adults to
sexually

30:16.948 --> 30:18.883 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
assault another student.

30:18.917 --> 30:24.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During a four-year period, the
AP tallied
at least 17,000 cases around the
country.

30:24.622 --> 30:29.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These included many cases that
were treated
as bullying or hazing instead.

30:29.527 --> 30:31.429 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Emily Schmall is a member of the
AP team.

30:31.462 --> 30:33.598 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She joins me now from Dallas.

30:33.631 --> 30:35.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Emily, thanks for joining us.

30:35.266 --> 30:40.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One key point you're making is
that this happens
more often than we know, right?

30:40.205 --> 30:42.807 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is it possible to say how
pervasive it is?

30:42.841 --> 30:45.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EMILY SCHMALL, Associated Press:
Yes, it's
absolutely true.

30:45.777 --> 30:49.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It happens far more often, I
think, than people
realize.

30:50.014 --> 30:56.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To say exactly how pervasive it
is, it's difficult
though, because, just like rape
and sexual

30:56.921 --> 31:04.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
assault perpetrated in other
places, rape
and sexual assault in schools is
definitely

31:04.262 --> 31:06.064 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
under-reported.

31:06.097 --> 31:11.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, while we have been able to
tally about
17,000 incidents over the four
years, experts

31:11.669 --> 31:13.471 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have told us it's just the tip
of the iceberg.

31:13.504 --> 31:16.107 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, let's
establish what we
are talking about.

31:16.140 --> 31:19.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Really, we're going beyond
bullying, beyond
hazing.

31:19.978 --> 31:21.779 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Tell us what you are looking at
exactly.

31:21.813 --> 31:22.981 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EMILY SCHMALL: Yes.

31:23.014 --> 31:27.452 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, we were very, very
deliberate in what
we counted.

31:27.485 --> 31:34.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we are looking at sexual
assault as defined
by the Justice Department, which
means forced

31:34.192 --> 31:43.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
intercourse or sodomy, forced
oral sex, the
most severe forms of sexual
assault.

31:43.268 --> 31:49.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We deliberately didn't include
categories
like sexual harassment or
bullying, even though,

31:49.841 --> 31:53.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as you noted, sometimes, sex
assaults are
reported as these things.

31:53.511 --> 31:57.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so if you
look at the
rules governing schools, I
gather that it

31:57.682 --> 32:02.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really varies from state to
state in terms
of how much this is tracked and
what kind

32:02.687 --> 32:03.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of actions are taken.

32:04.022 --> 32:07.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EMILY SCHMALL: Yes, and even
sometimes within
school districts.

32:07.392 --> 32:14.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's no federal requirement
that says schools
have to track student-on-student
sex assault,

32:14.532 --> 32:19.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
even though for a long time
schools have been
tracking things like free and
reduced lunch,

32:19.370 --> 32:22.774 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
guns, drugs on school property.

32:22.807 --> 32:27.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is just something that they
are not obligated
to track.

32:27.111 --> 32:33.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, various states do collect
some sort of
information, but it's
inconsistent state to

32:33.151 --> 32:34.886 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
state.

32:34.919 --> 32:38.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a lot of times, school
districts sort
of have the discretion over how
they report

32:39.023 --> 32:40.792 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
these things.

32:40.825 --> 32:46.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Therefore, in a case -- there
were plenty
of cases we found where they
have led to a

32:46.631 --> 32:54.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
criminal charge, but the act it
itself was
categorized and reported to the
state as bullying

32:54.405 --> 32:59.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or as sexual harassment or as a
lesser form
of sex offense.

32:59.544 --> 33:02.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You referred to
this a little
bit earlier, Emily.

33:02.280 --> 33:08.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just in terms of why these cases
float so
much under the radar, why we
know so little,

33:08.319 --> 33:10.054 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
spell that out a little bit.

33:10.088 --> 33:15.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMILY SCHMALL: Yes, so the
experts we spoke
to said there's just a real
reluctance on

33:15.526 --> 33:21.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the part of not only school
administrators,
but parents as well, to
acknowledge this for

33:21.566 --> 33:23.334 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
what it is.

33:23.368 --> 33:29.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They have a hard time
recognizing that kids
at such a young age can be
perpetrators or

33:29.841 --> 33:32.276 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be victimized in this way.

33:32.310 --> 33:34.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, that's part of it.

33:34.579 --> 33:41.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other part is that a lot of
schools have
said that they aren't really
aware of what

33:41.586 --> 33:48.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they are supposed to do when an
allegation
of sexual assault between
students surfaces.

33:48.459 --> 33:54.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, lastly, some experts
have actually
said that schools are just
looking after their

33:54.732 --> 33:57.468 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
public image more than they are
the victims.

33:57.502 --> 34:01.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, of course,
in the wider
public, it's just something hard
for all of

34:01.639 --> 34:03.941 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
us to want to even discuss, I
assume.

34:03.975 --> 34:05.810 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
EMILY SCHMALL: I think so.

34:05.843 --> 34:11.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, I think there's still
really a stigma
about sexual violence, not only
in the context

34:11.449 --> 34:15.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of K-12 schools, but in our
country at large.

34:15.820 --> 34:21.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So it's even more intense at the
younger school
level.

34:21.426 --> 34:24.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, so what can
or should
be done?

34:24.662 --> 34:26.764 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What -- for parents, for
educators?

34:26.798 --> 34:28.499 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What are the experts telling
you?

34:28.533 --> 34:32.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMILY SCHMALL: Well, the experts
are saying
that, you know, there is a real
reluctance

34:32.570 --> 34:39.610 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
among, not only school
administrators, but
parents as well, to acknowledge,
even, that

34:39.644 --> 34:44.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this is happening and that kids
of such a
young age are perpetrating these
kinds of

34:44.982 --> 34:46.517 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
offenses.

34:46.551 --> 34:51.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So the experts say that it needs
to be recognized
for what it is.

34:51.422 --> 34:57.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are a lot of people
working in the space
of how we solve this, how we
empower other

34:57.929 --> 34:59.597 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
kids to report it.

34:59.630 --> 35:04.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is actually something that
we're going
to be taking on later on in the
series.

35:04.469 --> 35:07.038 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Our stories are running every
Monday in May.

35:07.071 --> 35:11.609 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, Emily
Schmall of
the AP, thank you very much.

35:11.642 --> 35:18.950 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
EMILY SCHMALL: Thank you.

35:18.983 --> 35:25.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Turning back
